<br>
I have put the summary at the top of my work to prevent you from having to read all of the numbers in my case study.  I am sure this case study is not perfectly by the book, but as I only took 3 semesters of college, I will have to ask if you can bear with me.<br>
<br>
# =============================================================<br>
# Summary :<br>
This study was done to focus and address a number of questions.  After each of the questions I addressed during the study, I will present the results afterwords.<br>
<br>
This study was performed by having a control case study, were no stat buffs were on Hatrid, allowing for his base attack bonus to be logged.<br>
The second case study was where both the goblin skull and a strength spell (lvl 49 shaman spell) were applied to Hatrid.  <br>
The third case study was where the strength spell was not applied and just the goblin skull earring was used.<br>
<br>
1. Is there a difference to hit a yellow con mob when the attack value is increased? <br>
When facing yellow con mobs, there is no noticeable difference in an attack of a 918 and 998.<br>
The chances to hit the mob will vary up to 3% in between the tests, but this is easily attributed to just lucky (or unlucky) dice rolls in the case.  <br>
The chances to hit the mobs ranged from 52.1% up to 55.1%.  The reason why the variation on these numbers is due to chance is because the 55.1 percent hit rate was in the third case study where only the goblin skull earring was used.<br>
<br>
2. Is there a difference to hit a blue con mob when the attack value is increased? <br>
When facing blue con mobs, there was no noticeable difference in percentage chance to hit over the yellow con mobs.  There is no noticeable difference in the chances to hit a blue con mob given.  The chances vary in a 2.5% margin, and is not enough to be noticeable.<br>
<br>
3. Is there a noticeable difference in average damage (per swing) when fighting yellow vs blue con mobs?<br>
In each study case the amount of average damage varied no more than .8 amount of damage per hit.  This shows that there is no visiable difference in damage done to a yellow con or a blue con mob.<br>
<br>
4. Is there a noticeable difference in average damage (per swing) when having a str buff?<br>
When average damage is calculated, there is a slight increase in damage from the non strength buffed values.  This has also been described in many other research papers, and is expected.  This is because the max damage of a weapon has a direct corrolation on the strength of a user.  [((Weapon Skill + Strength)/100) * (DMG)) + (Level Damage Bonus)]<br>
In the largest variation, there is a 2.3 point difference in damage delt.  This is a 12.2% increase in damage from case one, and a 7.6% increase over case three.<br>
This is worth considering when applied to the 2248 swings done in the second case study, giving an average of 5170.4 more points of damage during that time.<br>
<br>
5. Is there a noticeable difference in average damage (per swing) when the goblin skull earring?<br>
There is an slight increase in damage output during that time, for a total of .6 more for each swing.  I am willing to attribue this to a random chance, but it does deserve future study.  <br>
<br>
6. Is there a noticeable value in the goblin skull earring?<br>
Currently there is no value shown in the grim aura that the goblin skull earring provides.  The extra buff looks good on your screen, and it can act as a buffer to your important buffs when you are having annul magic cast upon you.  (ie, standing in the middle of lake rathe in a duel and someone is attempting to remove your levitate buff)<br>
<br>
7. Is there a noticeable value in the lvl 49 shaman str buff?<br>
Yes.<br>
There definately appears to be a strong corrolation between an increased strength and a higher damage output per minute.<br>
<br>
